01:56.984 --> 01:59.588
♪ ♪

02:07.229 --> 02:09.031
(mechanical humming)

02:23.611 --> 02:27.148
(humming stops, resumes)

02:28.584 --> 02:31.038
(whispering): Oh, my God.

02:31.039 --> 02:32.208
- (click)
- (humming stops)

02:32.209 --> 02:33.476
Oh, my God.

02:33.477 --> 02:34.435
Hold still there,

02:34.436 --> 02:36.800
- please.
- (humming resumes)

02:36.801 --> 02:38.116
(humming stops)

02:42.670 --> 02:44.682
WOMAN: I don't... understand.

02:44.683 --> 02:46.984
MAN: It's a photograph, Anna,

02:46.985 --> 02:50.058
of the bones beneath your skin.

02:51.012 --> 02:52.578
Dear God, Wilhelm.

02:52.579 --> 02:53.793
I have seen

02:53.794 --> 02:55.327
my own death.

02:55.328 --> 02:58.173
It is wonderful, isn't it?

02:58.174 --> 03:00.347
Wilhelm...

03:00.348 --> 03:03.223
you are going to be famous.

03:03.224 --> 03:05.236
♪ ♪

03:05.237 --> 03:07.346
KATHARINA: I still
don't understand, Philipp.

03:07.347 --> 03:09.265
The invention is yours, is it not?

03:09.266 --> 03:11.790
The modification to the
cathode ray tube he used

03:11.791 --> 03:14.475
were my innovation, yes.

03:14.476 --> 03:17.063
This imposter, what's his name?

03:17.064 --> 03:19.270
- Rontgen.
- Well, if I read this article correctly,

03:19.271 --> 03:21.412
this Rontgen fellow
merely noticed something

03:21.413 --> 03:23.203
using <i>your</i> invention.

03:23.204 --> 03:25.759
He made an observation, yes.

03:25.760 --> 03:27.133
An observation.

03:27.134 --> 03:29.596
There. Taste your eggs.

03:29.597 --> 03:31.417
Make an observation about <i>them.</i>

03:31.418 --> 03:32.792
Too salty, perhaps?

03:32.793 --> 03:34.391
Does that mean you
cooked the damn things?

03:34.392 --> 03:35.573
- No.
- Of course not.

03:35.574 --> 03:37.875
Because to make such a claim
would be absurd.

03:37.876 --> 03:39.600
He's snatched the credit

03:39.601 --> 03:41.684
you justly deserve.

03:42.638 --> 03:44.619
(snaps newspaper)

03:44.620 --> 03:47.342
(exhales): How could I have missed it?

03:48.392 --> 03:50.118
You'll make it right, my love.

03:50.119 --> 03:51.717
I believe in you.

03:51.718 --> 03:55.015
Your brilliance will be recognized.

03:56.416 --> 03:58.652
EINSTEIN: <i>I don't care about awards,</i>

03:58.653 --> 04:00.731
Michele, I care about science,

04:00.732 --> 04:02.648
about understanding
the world around me.

04:02.649 --> 04:04.886
I'm not interested in shiny medals.

04:04.887 --> 04:07.476
This is not just any award...
it's called the Nobel Prize.

04:07.477 --> 04:10.128
Says here it is to be awarded
annually, and beyond notoriety

04:10.129 --> 04:11.535
it comes with a great deal of money.

04:11.536 --> 04:13.518
- Money?
- Just think...

04:13.519 --> 04:16.144
wealth and fame for being a physicist.

04:17.450 --> 04:19.783
You are brilliant, Albert,
you could win one.

04:19.784 --> 04:22.309
Right now I'd trade ten
of these Nobel Prizes

04:22.310 --> 04:24.322
for a teaching job.

04:24.323 --> 04:26.629
♪ ♪

04:28.350 --> 04:30.177
Steady.

04:32.252 --> 04:34.392
I've clearly miscalculated the salary

04:34.393 --> 04:35.991
- of an assistant professor.
- Don't be thick.

04:35.992 --> 04:38.452
I won it in a bet with the
head of my department.

04:38.453 --> 04:41.009
This sultry beast...
'tis only mine till sundown.

04:41.010 --> 04:43.054
- BESSO: What was the bet?
- I'm sure it's a riveting yarn,

04:43.055 --> 04:45.131
and I'm happy to suffer
through the whole damn thing

04:45.132 --> 04:46.890
once we're actually
on the road to Basel.

04:46.891 --> 04:48.457
My first interview,

04:48.458 --> 04:49.896
and I'm going to be late... perfect.

04:49.897 --> 04:51.844
Like a virginal maiden,
Albert, this machine needs

04:51.845 --> 04:55.202
to be delicately wooed
to a state of agitation.

04:55.203 --> 04:57.088
If Marcel's history with
the ladies is any predictor,

04:57.089 --> 04:59.422
we'll be on the road by next Tuesday.

04:59.423 --> 05:00.796
Albert, you will sweat

05:00.797 --> 05:02.427
through that suit if
you don't calm down.

05:02.428 --> 05:03.992
Michele, I have sent my paper

05:03.993 --> 05:05.750
to every halfway decent
university in Europe,

05:05.751 --> 05:07.189
and I've been rejected everywhere.

05:07.190 --> 05:09.299
This is the first bite
of the apple I've had.

05:09.300 --> 05:10.674
Mileva's getting impatient.

05:10.675 --> 05:13.135
Mileva? She's in Serbia...
what does she have...?

05:13.136 --> 05:14.414
- (engine starts)
- Ah!

05:14.415 --> 05:16.811
An historic day... Marcel Grossmann

05:16.812 --> 05:18.538
finally gets something
all hot and bothered.

05:18.539 --> 05:19.918
Ah...

05:21.735 --> 05:23.140
(exhales)

05:23.141 --> 05:25.443
MAN: <i>The capillary effect has been</i>

05:25.444 --> 05:27.361
well studied, Herr Einstein.

05:27.362 --> 05:29.279
Your disquisition hardly adds

05:29.280 --> 05:31.163
to the body of knowledge.

05:31.164 --> 05:33.401
To say nothing of your verbose style.

05:33.402 --> 05:37.499
The reading experience
is undeniably taxing.

05:39.221 --> 05:41.522
I would be remiss

05:41.523 --> 05:45.101
to challenge your opinions,
Herr Professor.

05:45.102 --> 05:47.248
Science is not about opinions.

05:48.460 --> 05:51.782
What I mean to say,
Herr Professor, is...

05:51.783 --> 05:55.746
you make many observations
I hadn't considered,

05:55.747 --> 05:57.728
much to my regret.

05:57.729 --> 05:59.332
(chuckles softly)

06:00.862 --> 06:03.898
Your record does you credit,
I must admit.

06:03.899 --> 06:05.976
And despite a large field

06:05.977 --> 06:09.428
of gifted applicants, it
seems that you're somehow

06:09.429 --> 06:12.082
the most qualified
candidate we've yet met.

06:12.083 --> 06:13.393
I shall send your name

06:13.394 --> 06:14.997
up to the committee for approval.

06:16.367 --> 06:17.900
Thank you.

06:17.901 --> 06:19.466
Thank... thank you.

06:19.467 --> 06:21.896
MILEVA: <i>Albert hasn't
abandoned me, Papa.</i>

06:21.897 --> 06:23.494
Then where is he?

06:23.495 --> 06:25.093
Tell me that.

06:25.094 --> 06:26.626
Getting settled.

06:26.627 --> 06:30.016
I need a home to return to
once I've had the baby.

06:30.017 --> 06:31.581
And then what?

06:31.582 --> 06:34.203
Miza. Then what?

06:34.204 --> 06:36.440
You change diapers all day long?

06:36.441 --> 06:38.486
Wipe noses?

06:38.487 --> 06:40.117
Sing lullabies?

06:40.118 --> 06:42.418
No. I will earn my degree, Papa.

06:42.419 --> 06:44.497
- I swear it.
- For years,

06:44.498 --> 06:47.725
I taught you never to rely
on a man for <i>anything.</i>

06:47.726 --> 06:50.953
Do I really need to explain
the situation to you, Papa?

06:50.954 --> 06:53.191
I just don't want you
to punish yourself

06:53.192 --> 06:55.301
for the rest of your life.

06:55.302 --> 06:57.827
Not for making a mistake one night.

06:57.828 --> 07:00.416
It wasn't a mistake.

07:00.417 --> 07:03.459
And it certainly wasn't one night.

07:06.105 --> 07:08.471
You were in Zurich...
the Swiss are experts

07:08.472 --> 07:11.189
at taking care of
unfortunate circumstances.

07:11.190 --> 07:13.107
I would never do such a thing!

07:13.108 --> 07:16.463
I <i>want</i> to have Albert's child.

07:16.464 --> 07:19.083
(shudders) I want more for you.

07:19.084 --> 07:20.938
If you believe in me,

07:20.939 --> 07:23.597
Papa, at least give Albert a chance.

07:24.326 --> 07:26.276
♪ ♪

07:26.277 --> 07:27.587
(door opens)

07:27.588 --> 07:29.031
(door slams)

07:32.352 --> 07:34.881
(hinges squeak)

07:37.626 --> 07:39.064
(door opens)

07:39.065 --> 07:40.534
(door creaks)

07:40.535 --> 07:42.648
Herr Einstein.

07:43.476 --> 07:46.192
Good evening, Frau Schnellham.

07:46.193 --> 07:48.430
You're quite the kitty,
sneaking all about.

07:48.431 --> 07:51.689
Just testing your impeccable hearing.

07:51.690 --> 07:53.481
Still top-notch.

07:53.482 --> 07:54.727
Do you have the rent or not?

07:54.728 --> 07:55.846
Not.

07:55.847 --> 07:57.060
You know your way out, then,

07:57.061 --> 07:58.978
- kitty.
- I've secured a position.

07:58.979 --> 08:00.162
I'm merely awaiting

08:00.163 --> 08:01.407
a final letter of approval.

08:01.408 --> 08:03.644
Then it isn't secured, is it?

08:03.645 --> 08:05.115
Well, perhaps there's word today.

08:05.116 --> 08:07.067
I-I would check the post, but...

08:07.068 --> 08:08.665
seeing as you've confiscated

08:08.666 --> 08:11.157
my mail key...

08:11.158 --> 08:12.884
Please, Frau Schnellham.

08:12.885 --> 08:14.615
(sighs)

08:17.744 --> 08:21.036
Many prominent academics and
leading thinkers in the field

08:21.037 --> 08:23.821
are talking favorably of my work.

08:31.361 --> 08:32.960
(opening envelope)

08:32.961 --> 08:34.244
Well?

08:36.380 --> 08:38.616
EINSTEIN: <i>I was given the impression</i>

08:38.618 --> 08:40.951
<i>that the job was mine
but for a formality.</i>

08:40.952 --> 08:43.604
I've made many inquiries
in search of answers,

08:43.605 --> 08:45.714
but I've been met with silence.

08:45.715 --> 08:47.952
So you have come for help, then.

08:47.953 --> 08:50.924
Just... a small favor,

08:50.925 --> 08:52.683
Herr Professor,
a letter of recommendation,

08:52.684 --> 08:53.673
perhaps.

08:53.674 --> 08:54.825
Perhaps, uh, like,

08:54.826 --> 08:56.455
uh, this one.

08:56.456 --> 08:57.637
(clears throat)

08:57.638 --> 09:00.386
"Esteemed Herr Weber,
forgive my impudence

09:00.387 --> 09:02.337
"in writing you directly,

09:02.338 --> 09:06.939
"but I beg you to intercede
on behalf of my poor Albert.

09:06.940 --> 09:08.505
As a concerned father..."

09:08.506 --> 09:09.918
My father?

09:13.301 --> 09:15.960
Herr Professor, I...

09:16.883 --> 09:18.800
I had no idea.

09:18.801 --> 09:21.070
I would... I would never ask my father

09:21.071 --> 09:22.987
to intercede on my behalf.

09:22.988 --> 09:24.713
Frankly, I'm mortified.

09:24.714 --> 09:26.472
As you should be.

09:26.473 --> 09:29.668
Like any other recent graduate,
I am only asking

09:29.669 --> 09:31.714
that you put in a word
with potential employers.

09:31.715 --> 09:33.056
Oh, but I have.

09:33.057 --> 09:35.039
Many universities
have sought my counsel

09:35.040 --> 09:37.179
on your intellect and your character.

09:37.180 --> 09:39.065
But in good conscience

09:39.066 --> 09:41.208
I have not and I <i>cannot...</i>

09:41.209 --> 09:43.322
recommend your character.

09:44.534 --> 09:47.537
You gave me an unfavorable
recommendation?

09:47.538 --> 09:48.976
Several, in fact.

09:48.977 --> 09:50.286
But that's sabotage.

09:50.287 --> 09:52.460
You openly challenged my authority.

09:52.461 --> 09:54.378
You publicly disrespected me.

09:54.379 --> 09:57.798
How am I to justify sticking
my head above the grass for you

09:57.799 --> 09:59.684
when there are so many qualified alumni

09:59.685 --> 10:01.314
who have actually earned my respect?

10:01.315 --> 10:03.424
But this is my reputation
we're talking about.

10:03.425 --> 10:04.676
And mine, too!

10:05.888 --> 10:07.867
If I recommend someone
and they fail to live up

10:07.868 --> 10:10.266
to my endorsement, how do <i>I</i> look?

10:10.267 --> 10:11.352
But you don't understand, sir.

10:11.353 --> 10:14.357
I have... I have obligations.

10:14.358 --> 10:17.553
(chuckles) Obligations.

10:17.554 --> 10:19.663
You are what? 22?

10:19.664 --> 10:22.764
An unknown, unattached,
healthy young man.

10:22.765 --> 10:25.487
What obligations could
you possibly have?

10:27.624 --> 10:30.021
EINSTEIN: <i>My name is ruined!
All because I couldn't keep</i>

10:30.022 --> 10:32.195
my stupid mouth shut in Weber's class.

10:32.196 --> 10:35.199
I already wrote to Mileva
to tell her I got the job.

10:35.200 --> 10:37.470
Mileva? What has she
got to do with this?

10:37.471 --> 10:40.122
Put in a good word for me,
Marcel, in your department.

10:40.123 --> 10:42.520
I am a flea on the
smelly ass of academia.

10:42.521 --> 10:44.630
No one cares what I have to say.

10:44.631 --> 10:46.867
But there is a position I know of.

10:46.868 --> 10:48.786
Decent wage, steady hours.

10:48.787 --> 10:50.384
What is it?

10:50.385 --> 10:52.301
It's in Bern at the patent office.

10:52.302 --> 10:54.220
Um, clerical position,
but very interesting work.

10:54.221 --> 10:56.425
You could employ some of
your engineering knowledge.

10:56.426 --> 10:57.864
I'm a scientist, Marcel!

10:57.865 --> 10:59.206
I'm better than a clerkship.

10:59.207 --> 11:01.444
- You need money.
- I need a thought,

11:01.445 --> 11:04.705
a paper that can show people
what I can do; I need time.

11:04.706 --> 11:06.367
No, you need a job.

11:06.368 --> 11:07.837
Why not ask your father

11:07.838 --> 11:10.491
could he set you up
in the factory in Milan?

11:10.492 --> 11:12.217
Because he humiliated me.

11:12.218 --> 11:14.134
I'm done with him, after
the letter to Weber.

11:14.135 --> 11:16.693
Did it ever occur to you
that perhaps your father

11:16.694 --> 11:19.250
reached out to Weber because
he cares about you?

11:19.251 --> 11:20.624
Be practical, Albert.

11:20.625 --> 11:22.765
If you will not get a real job,

11:22.766 --> 11:24.748
how on earth will you survive?

11:24.749 --> 11:26.352
Hmm?

11:32.069 --> 11:34.184
♪ ♪

11:34.979 --> 11:37.093
MAN: Whoa.

11:44.984 --> 11:46.261
Maja.

11:46.262 --> 11:48.211
Big brother.

11:48.212 --> 11:49.490
We missed you in Milan.

11:49.491 --> 11:50.801
I thought it would be best

11:50.802 --> 11:52.111
to meet you and Mother here.

11:52.112 --> 11:53.998
Because Father is not with us?

11:53.999 --> 11:55.308
You can't ignore him forever.

11:55.309 --> 11:57.002
He's hurt, Albert.

11:57.003 --> 12:00.423
I'm... I'm not ready to face him.

12:00.424 --> 12:03.427
Not until you feel you've
made something of yourself.

12:03.428 --> 12:06.912
Only then will you be able to
tell him he was wrong about you?

12:06.913 --> 12:08.575
How's Mother?

12:08.576 --> 12:10.396
Did you really have to send her

12:10.397 --> 12:12.155
a photo of your Serbian temptress?

12:12.156 --> 12:14.104
I thought she might like it.

12:14.105 --> 12:16.374
What she really liked was Marie.

12:16.375 --> 12:18.420
She was counting on
you two getting married,

12:18.421 --> 12:20.977
so don't mention Mileva.

12:20.978 --> 12:22.964
(sighs)

12:24.974 --> 12:27.723
PAULINE: Tell me everything
that's been happening.

12:27.724 --> 12:30.631
I'm sure the world is
beating down your door.

12:30.632 --> 12:33.348
I'm, uh, developing many new ideas.

12:33.349 --> 12:35.010
Won't be long before I'm
recognized for my work.

12:35.011 --> 12:36.129
(chuckles)

12:36.130 --> 12:38.464
But, um,

12:38.465 --> 12:40.158
right now, Mother,

12:40.159 --> 12:43.041
the-the truth is, I need money.

12:45.720 --> 12:47.317
Your father's business

12:47.318 --> 12:49.748
needed another infusion
of capital, darling.

12:49.749 --> 12:51.569
I can't go to my brother again.

12:51.570 --> 12:54.286
I'm afraid the well is dry.

12:54.287 --> 12:56.173
You'll have to manage on your own.

12:56.174 --> 12:57.804
If there's such
pressing money concerns,

12:57.805 --> 13:00.040
then why are you taking
such lavish holidays?

13:00.041 --> 13:01.575
Lower your voice, dear.

13:01.576 --> 13:04.772
We must keep up appearances.

13:04.773 --> 13:07.552
If only Marie were here
to teach you some manners.

13:07.553 --> 13:08.767
Marie and I are finished.

13:08.768 --> 13:10.173
And it seems to me, if you apologize

13:10.174 --> 13:11.485
for your boorish behavior,

13:11.486 --> 13:12.892
you may have a chance to win her back.

13:12.893 --> 13:14.585
Mother, you know very well

13:14.586 --> 13:16.472
that I have someone else now.

13:16.473 --> 13:18.550
What? That creature
in the photo you sent?

13:18.551 --> 13:21.682
- She isn't even Jewish.
- Neither is Marie.

13:21.683 --> 13:23.056
Well, at least she isn't Slavic.

13:23.057 --> 13:24.303
- What does that mean?
- Mother.

13:24.304 --> 13:26.477
- Be... She'll be the end of you,
- Albert.

13:26.478 --> 13:28.172
She's just a nasty little witch.

13:28.173 --> 13:29.258
She is no witch.

13:29.259 --> 13:31.687
She's my wife.

13:31.688 --> 13:33.228
(gasps)

13:37.059 --> 13:39.136
Oh.

13:39.137 --> 13:41.315
(crying)

13:43.165 --> 13:44.922
You married that girl?

13:44.923 --> 13:46.329
No, of course not.

13:46.330 --> 13:48.598
Then why did you say that you did?

13:48.599 --> 13:51.474
Because I can't stand the way
that Mother talks about Mileva

13:51.475 --> 13:53.744
and I don't want to give
her the satisfaction

13:53.745 --> 13:55.183
of thinking she can tell me what to do.

13:55.184 --> 13:57.842
So then you're not marrying Mileva.

14:01.994 --> 14:04.071
(sighs)

14:04.072 --> 14:06.377
I'm going to have to.

14:08.419 --> 14:11.805
How... How far along is she?

14:11.806 --> 14:15.066
- Six months.
- God, Albert.

14:15.067 --> 14:17.719
I don't know what I'm supposed to say.
Congratulations?

14:17.720 --> 14:19.574
Are you happy about this?

14:19.575 --> 14:23.121
I love her, Maja.

14:23.122 --> 14:26.830
She's-She's like nobody
I've ever met before.

14:26.831 --> 14:31.081
I felt this... this pull towards her.

14:31.082 --> 14:35.525
Since I saw her, I...
I should be thrilled, but...

14:35.526 --> 14:36.644
But?

14:36.645 --> 14:37.923
Well, now I feel this opposing force

14:37.924 --> 14:40.160
pulling me down.

14:40.161 --> 14:42.397
I'm just getting started with my life.

14:42.398 --> 14:45.308
I'm-I'm worried that if I marry her,

14:45.309 --> 14:49.813
I'll never take flight.

14:49.814 --> 14:52.728
What other choice do you have?

15:02.332 --> 15:03.502
You have a visitor.

15:03.503 --> 15:04.973
MILEVA: A visitor? But who could...?

15:04.974 --> 15:07.337
Sir.

15:07.338 --> 15:09.382
This is quite unexpected.

15:09.383 --> 15:10.980
My dear, it is wonderful to see you.

15:10.981 --> 15:14.783
I would stand,
but you may remember my hip.

15:14.784 --> 15:16.701
It's been acting up.

15:16.702 --> 15:17.693
Yes, of course.

15:17.694 --> 15:19.129
I have to say I was overjoyed

15:19.130 --> 15:21.175
when your father paid a visit

15:21.176 --> 15:24.627
to inform me that my finest
student was back in town.

15:24.628 --> 15:28.205
But I have to admit this is
not merely a social call.

15:28.206 --> 15:30.283
- No?
- I am here

15:30.284 --> 15:32.234
to offer you a teaching position

15:32.235 --> 15:33.896
for the spring term.

15:33.897 --> 15:36.227
It is time we had a woman

15:36.228 --> 15:38.530
on the permanent faculty.

15:38.531 --> 15:40.703
It is a new era.

15:40.704 --> 15:42.972
MILEVA: <i>How could you
ambush me like that?</i>

15:42.973 --> 15:45.208
What if he'd seen my belly?

15:45.209 --> 15:46.902
My secret would be out.

15:46.903 --> 15:48.181
Calm yourself, Mileva.

15:48.182 --> 15:49.810
I just wanted you to know

15:49.811 --> 15:51.248
that there is an alternative.

15:51.249 --> 15:54.030
Einstein used to write you every day.

15:54.031 --> 15:56.009
Now it's once a week at most.

15:56.010 --> 15:59.878
He's... he's very busy, Papa.

15:59.879 --> 16:01.762
Or maybe he has lost interest?

16:01.763 --> 16:03.520
You deduced all of that

16:03.521 --> 16:05.629
by the frequency of his letters?

16:05.630 --> 16:08.857
And so now you want me to
settle for being a schoolmarm?

16:08.858 --> 16:10.776
Perhaps you could teach physics?

16:10.777 --> 16:14.840
You could use the skills
you have learned.

16:20.139 --> 16:23.687
Are you giving up on me, Papa?

16:23.688 --> 16:26.115
I'm giving up on Einstein.

16:26.116 --> 16:28.033
He can't even get a job.

16:28.034 --> 16:30.271
You're wrong.

16:30.272 --> 16:31.803
He has a job.

16:31.804 --> 16:33.503
- Yeah.
- Teaching.

16:34.265 --> 16:37.237
But what is the ether?

16:37.238 --> 16:41.045
What kind of substance has
such remarkable properties?

16:42.863 --> 16:45.610
One has to twist all
of physics into knots

16:45.611 --> 16:47.367
just to make it work,
but it must exist, or else...

16:47.368 --> 16:49.801
Are you a Jew?

16:52.737 --> 16:54.909
I subscribe to no religion.

16:54.910 --> 16:56.642
You look like a Jew.

16:57.691 --> 16:59.864
Are you sliced? Down there?

16:59.865 --> 17:02.037
Does it feel odd to fornicate

17:02.038 --> 17:03.544
if you're sliced?

17:05.137 --> 17:08.779
Timo, your father isn't paying
me to tutor you

17:08.780 --> 17:12.262
about the ins and outs of...
about girls,

17:12.262 --> 17:14.405
but if you'll indulge me,

17:14.406 --> 17:16.545
I'll show you that mathematics

17:16.546 --> 17:18.846
is as elegant as the finest of women,

17:18.847 --> 17:21.116
and just like women,

17:21.117 --> 17:23.127
it might seem intimidating at first,

17:23.128 --> 17:26.037
but the truth is anyone can do it.

17:26.038 --> 17:27.635
LENARD: <i>Almost anyone
with rudimentary learning</i>

17:27.636 --> 17:29.392
could achieve the same results.

17:29.393 --> 17:31.278
All these prints were taken by me

17:31.279 --> 17:33.037
using my own tubes, not Rontgen's.

17:33.038 --> 17:37.511
It's one thing that you were
able to duplicate his outcome,

17:37.512 --> 17:39.556
but are you implying that Rontgen

17:39.557 --> 17:41.250
actually poached your tube model?

17:41.251 --> 17:44.285
Sir, not only did he
appropriate my design,

17:44.286 --> 17:46.971
he wrote to me asking for supplies.

17:46.972 --> 17:49.654
Supplies which are very
difficult to come by,

17:49.655 --> 17:51.796
and I did graciously comply.

17:51.797 --> 17:53.713
Only to be stabbed in the back,

17:53.714 --> 17:57.006
flank and front for my selfless deed.

17:57.007 --> 17:59.146
Yes, but why should any of
this concern the academy?

17:59.147 --> 18:00.552
LENARD: Professor Plom,

18:00.553 --> 18:02.502
the Nobel Committee is
considering candidates.

18:02.503 --> 18:04.643
If Rontgen receives recognition

18:04.644 --> 18:06.432
for something that isn't all his,

18:06.433 --> 18:09.149
then the entire fabric of this
institution is under attack.

18:09.150 --> 18:11.419
Unlike Rontgen,

18:11.420 --> 18:13.209
I'm seeking neither fame nor money.

18:13.210 --> 18:15.029
I am defending science itself.

18:15.030 --> 18:17.906
PLOM: What specifically
are you asking us to do?

18:17.907 --> 18:21.102
Compose a letter of support
to the Nobel Committee, hmm?

18:21.103 --> 18:22.732
Immediately.

18:22.733 --> 18:25.805
May we have the room, Philipp?

18:26.600 --> 18:28.554
Hmm, yeah.

18:31.808 --> 18:33.022
(door closes)

18:33.023 --> 18:35.386
He's bringing politics into science.

18:35.387 --> 18:36.761
I can't condone it.

18:36.762 --> 18:38.199
It's beneath us all.

18:38.200 --> 18:39.797
PLOM: Still, imagine how we would feel

18:39.798 --> 18:42.258
if an inferior talent
snatched recognition

18:42.259 --> 18:44.175
for one of our achievements.

18:44.176 --> 18:47.824
A bit of ink, it costs us nothing.

18:49.706 --> 18:51.942
ALBERT: <i>Dearest Mileva,</i>

18:51.943 --> 18:55.297
<i>I understand you're upset
I haven't written,</i>

18:55.298 --> 18:56.640
<i>but I've been terribly busy.</i>

18:56.641 --> 18:57.919
<i>And while I'd love nothing more</i>

18:57.920 --> 19:00.251
<i>than to have you visit,</i>

19:00.252 --> 19:02.711
<i>I haven't had time to
furnish my new dwelling.</i>

19:02.712 --> 19:04.310
<i>If you still wish to rendezvous,</i>

19:04.311 --> 19:06.035
<i>I only request it be somewhere</i>

19:06.036 --> 19:07.952
<i>discreet to avoid gossip.</i>

19:07.953 --> 19:09.710
MARIJA A secluded inn.

19:09.711 --> 19:11.755
As if your present situation
weren't scandal enough.

19:11.756 --> 19:12.970
Mama, please.

19:12.971 --> 19:14.344
It's only for a few days.

19:14.345 --> 19:15.910
A few days.

19:15.911 --> 19:17.764
An unmarried, pregnant woman
traveling on her own.

19:17.765 --> 19:19.496
What will people say?

19:29.526 --> 19:31.281
Your name, madam?

19:31.282 --> 19:33.073
Mileva Einstein.

19:33.074 --> 19:36.945
My husband should have already arrived.

19:37.707 --> 19:40.172
No, I don't believe so.

19:41.957 --> 19:43.778
If you'd just show me to my room,

19:43.779 --> 19:45.856
I've had a very
exhausting day of travel.

19:45.857 --> 19:49.723
My husband had business to transact.

19:49.724 --> 19:52.445
He'll arrive any moment.

19:53.463 --> 19:55.410
Please.

19:55.411 --> 19:57.494
(speaks indistinctly)

20:00.045 --> 20:01.963
(thunder rumbles)

20:01.964 --> 20:04.078
♪ ♪

20:23.440 --> 20:25.553
(footsteps approaching)

20:26.700 --> 20:28.814
(knocking on door)

20:33.155 --> 20:34.848
Herr Ebersold.

20:34.849 --> 20:36.605
Forgetting something, Einstein?

20:36.606 --> 20:39.321
Oh, God, yes, actually.
I'm late for my train.

20:39.322 --> 20:42.199
I mean Timo, Einstein.

20:42.200 --> 20:43.573
My boy.

20:43.574 --> 20:44.946
You were scheduled to
tutor him this afternoon.

20:44.947 --> 20:47.152
I'll make it up to you, sir.

20:47.153 --> 20:48.622
I'm not finished,

20:48.623 --> 20:51.216
Herr Einstein.

20:56.644 --> 20:59.168
His marks are lower
than when you started.

20:59.169 --> 21:02.811
What are you teaching
the boy, Einstein?

21:02.812 --> 21:05.079
Well, we have touched occasionally

21:05.080 --> 21:07.350
on subjects, I admit,

21:07.351 --> 21:10.864
that are a bit ambitious.

21:10.865 --> 21:12.143
Yes, Timo told me.

21:12.144 --> 21:14.157
Heat transfers, ether,

21:14.158 --> 21:16.584
hypothetical atoms,
something called quanta.

21:16.585 --> 21:18.375
He needed help with algebra.

21:18.376 --> 21:22.082
But what good is algebra
if you have no understanding

21:22.083 --> 21:25.661
of how it applies to the
larger questions of science?

21:25.662 --> 21:28.161
You're fired, Einstein.

21:32.598 --> 21:35.090
(footsteps receding)

21:35.091 --> 21:37.007
(door opens)

21:37.008 --> 21:39.122
(door closes)

21:47.714 --> 21:50.371
(door opens)

21:52.188 --> 21:55.064
Where have you been?

21:55.065 --> 21:57.173
I'm so sorry, I was... (clears throat)

21:57.174 --> 21:58.994
I was working and then-then

21:58.995 --> 22:00.687
I got, uh, distracted,
and when I looked up...

22:00.688 --> 22:02.509
How could you leave me here?

22:02.510 --> 22:04.875
Do you have any idea what it's
like to be a pregnant woman

22:04.876 --> 22:06.440
traveling this country alone?

22:06.441 --> 22:07.687
Dollie.

22:07.688 --> 22:09.285
Of course you don't.

22:09.286 --> 22:10.979
I'm so stupid.

22:10.980 --> 22:12.992
No, you're not stupid.
You're brilliant. Come on.

22:12.993 --> 22:14.782
Look, I'm here now,

22:14.783 --> 22:16.858
and that's what's important, my love.

22:16.859 --> 22:20.854
Let me explain, you'll
understand everything.

22:20.855 --> 22:23.703
Radiation quanta.

22:25.809 --> 22:28.844
Planck's concept.

22:28.845 --> 22:30.728
Radiation quanta?

22:30.729 --> 22:32.039
This could be the breakthrough

22:32.040 --> 22:33.478
that I've been searching for.

22:33.479 --> 22:36.385
You didn't come to be with me,

22:36.386 --> 22:39.837
you came to use me
to help you with math.

22:39.838 --> 22:41.500
No, I was...

22:41.501 --> 22:43.225
Why did I expect any different?

22:43.226 --> 22:45.908
You-you write page after page
about work in your letters,

22:45.909 --> 22:47.955
but you almost never ask about me.

22:47.956 --> 22:50.064
- That isn't true.
- I search endlessly

22:50.065 --> 22:52.364
for some caring emotion

22:52.365 --> 22:54.890
like a pig digging for truffles,

22:54.891 --> 22:58.725
but I never find it.

22:58.726 --> 23:01.441
At least I know my father
was right about one thing.

23:01.442 --> 23:02.975
- And what's that?
- You're too damn selfish

23:02.976 --> 23:04.509
to be a good husband.

23:04.510 --> 23:07.864
I've defended you to everyone.

23:07.865 --> 23:10.421
And now I feel like a fool.

23:10.422 --> 23:11.987
None of them have ever met you,

23:11.988 --> 23:14.480
and yet they saw you
more clearly than I did.

23:14.481 --> 23:15.631
That's nonsense. Mileva, do you...

23:15.632 --> 23:16.813
You're having my child.

23:16.814 --> 23:18.635
And what a mistake that was.

23:18.636 --> 23:20.649
I'll live with the consequences

23:20.650 --> 23:23.012
forever.

23:23.013 --> 23:26.369
But at least the child and I
won't have you to let us down.

23:26.370 --> 23:27.456
What are you saying?

23:27.457 --> 23:30.050
I'm fairly certain I just said it.

23:31.451 --> 23:34.678
Don't act like you want to marry me.

23:34.679 --> 23:37.560
I know you don't.

23:57.944 --> 24:00.052
I missed the train
because I was distracted.

24:00.053 --> 24:02.034
I couldn't wait

24:02.035 --> 24:04.911
to share my ideas with you.

24:04.912 --> 24:08.171
Not because they promise
glory for me, but because...

24:08.172 --> 24:12.804
it was like peeking through
a keyhole to our future.

24:12.805 --> 24:15.936
The two of us. Huh?

24:15.937 --> 24:18.174
Mileva...

24:18.175 --> 24:21.407
you're the love of my life.

24:22.552 --> 24:24.788
And I will do the right thing for you

24:24.789 --> 24:26.387
and this child.

24:26.388 --> 24:28.278
I promise.

24:49.049 --> 24:51.829
GROSSMANN: <i>"Private lessons
in mathematics and physics,</i>

24:51.830 --> 24:54.384
<i>"given most thoroughly
by Albert Einstein.</i>

24:54.385 --> 24:56.366
Trial lesson free."

24:56.367 --> 24:57.900
Sounds promising.

24:57.901 --> 24:59.434
This is a new low, Albert.

24:59.435 --> 25:01.416
It's just temporary till
I find something better.

25:01.417 --> 25:03.077
GROSSMANN: If you're in such straits,

25:03.078 --> 25:05.092
the job in the patent
office is still open, and...

25:05.093 --> 25:05.890
I'm a scientist.

25:05.891 --> 25:07.902
I'm not a damn clerk.

25:07.903 --> 25:09.501
I just need time
to finish my new paper.

25:09.502 --> 25:10.747
Paper?

25:10.748 --> 25:12.798
What paper, Albert?

25:13.624 --> 25:15.924
Radiation packets.

25:15.925 --> 25:18.130
Planck calls them "quanta."

25:18.131 --> 25:20.335
You do realize that radiation quanta

25:20.336 --> 25:22.157
is an academic idea.
Planck himself does not believe

25:22.158 --> 25:24.042
- they describe reality.
- Planck himself is wrong.

25:24.043 --> 25:25.511
- (chuckles)
- You'll see.

25:25.512 --> 25:27.788
Someone else can rot
in a patent office.

25:34.077 --> 25:36.698
MAN: Albert Einstein?

25:36.699 --> 25:38.711
Maurice Solovine.

25:38.712 --> 25:40.629
How do you do?

25:40.630 --> 25:42.705
Sir, if I owe you money,

25:42.706 --> 25:45.774
then I'm afraid you'll
have to get in line.

25:45.775 --> 25:49.097
Are you not Albert Einstein?

25:49.098 --> 25:52.836
You are here for physics?

25:52.837 --> 25:54.210
Indeed.

25:54.211 --> 25:56.128
But recreationally.

25:56.129 --> 25:57.983
My friends accuse me of
being a bored dilettante,

25:57.984 --> 26:00.506
to which I plead guilty as charged.

26:00.507 --> 26:02.936
I've studied biology, philosophy,

26:02.937 --> 26:04.438
literature, art.

26:04.439 --> 26:07.185
Physics is the next logical subject

26:07.186 --> 26:09.615
in my illogical curriculum.

26:09.616 --> 26:11.660
I think I have room in my schedule.

26:11.661 --> 26:12.939
When would you like to start?

26:12.940 --> 26:14.824
I'm here now, Einstein.

26:14.825 --> 26:16.421
The first lesson is free, Herr...

26:16.422 --> 26:17.796
(inhales): What was your name again?

26:17.797 --> 26:20.737
Solovine.

26:20.738 --> 26:23.964
I tell you what. I'll pay anyway,

26:23.965 --> 26:25.435
provided you submit

26:25.436 --> 26:27.639
to a change of venue.

26:27.640 --> 26:31.378
SOLOVINE: <i>The previous occupant</i>

26:31.379 --> 26:33.296
has done a garish rococo treatment,

26:33.297 --> 26:35.757
so I will spend a good
chunk of my father's money

26:35.758 --> 26:37.994
scraping the fairy tale
out of the place.

26:37.995 --> 26:40.103
(sighs): Here's the wine.

26:40.104 --> 26:41.894
Now, where are the
women to pour it over?

26:41.895 --> 26:43.010
(laughs)

26:43.011 --> 26:44.802
Albert, this is Conrad Habicht.

26:44.803 --> 26:46.814
Lout, wretch,

26:46.815 --> 26:50.010
altogether bad influence,
and my brother-in-arms.

26:50.011 --> 26:52.440
Conrad, this is Albert Einstein,

26:52.441 --> 26:53.846
the most promising,

26:53.847 --> 26:56.722
illustrious young physicist
of his generation.

26:56.723 --> 26:58.607
Mmm. Well, I just hope he's better

26:58.608 --> 27:00.110
than that horrid fencing instructor

27:00.111 --> 27:01.260
you wasted our money on.

27:01.261 --> 27:02.601
Damn near impaled myself.

27:02.602 --> 27:04.231
- (laughs)
- (sighs)

27:04.232 --> 27:05.797
Well, come on, Einstein.

27:05.798 --> 27:09.569
We are your captive audience.

27:09.570 --> 27:11.870
Go on, Einstein.

27:11.871 --> 27:14.362
Dazzle us.

27:14.363 --> 27:16.855
(clears throat)

27:16.856 --> 27:18.491
D-Dazzle.

27:20.211 --> 27:22.129
Y-Yes, right.

27:22.130 --> 27:23.695
Uh, well... Um.

27:23.696 --> 27:25.038
(smacks lips) Uh...

27:25.039 --> 27:26.250
Liquids.

27:26.251 --> 27:28.169
Yes? They run in a tube.

27:28.170 --> 27:29.510
They tend to... They rise

27:29.511 --> 27:31.268
because of what is termed
the capillary effect...

27:31.269 --> 27:33.121
I've got a physics question.

27:33.122 --> 27:35.423
So, I was in my bathtub this morning,

27:35.424 --> 27:37.980
and I dunk my head at the same time

27:37.981 --> 27:40.057
as I knock my hairbrush in with my toe.

27:40.058 --> 27:42.742
And it hits the cast
iron, and it sounds

27:42.743 --> 27:43.893
quite loud underwater.

27:43.894 --> 27:46.066
Why is that?

27:46.067 --> 27:47.983
Well, um... Indulge me

27:47.984 --> 27:51.281
in something that I like to
call a thought experiment.

27:53.673 --> 27:55.654
Let's make waves.

27:55.655 --> 27:58.529
- A hammer hits a string,
- (both mouthing)

27:58.530 --> 27:59.872
causing a vibration

27:59.873 --> 28:03.393
which spreads out as a waveform.

28:06.200 --> 28:09.618
In this case, the medium is
a disturbance of the air,

28:09.619 --> 28:12.111
which, when it hits your eardrums,

28:12.112 --> 28:15.020
is interpreted as sound.

28:15.021 --> 28:16.489
Unlike matter,

28:16.490 --> 28:18.247
waves travel better
through denser materials.

28:18.248 --> 28:20.517
That's why your hairbrush sounded loud.

28:20.518 --> 28:21.731
Put your ears to a rail,

28:21.732 --> 28:23.201
and you can hear locomotives

28:23.202 --> 28:25.566
from miles away when all is silent

28:25.567 --> 28:27.291
an inch above the track.

28:27.292 --> 28:28.506
That's...

28:28.507 --> 28:29.944
- fantastic.
- Yes.

28:29.945 --> 28:32.086
But do you want to know what
I've really been thinking about?

28:32.087 --> 28:33.844
It's light,

28:33.845 --> 28:37.838
because light from
this candelabra, say,

28:37.839 --> 28:41.929
is a wave, just like sound.

28:41.930 --> 28:46.402
But if waves travel better
through denser materials,

28:46.403 --> 28:49.982
then why can I put up my hand

28:49.983 --> 28:52.417
and block out the brightest of lights?

28:53.179 --> 28:55.574
SOLOVINE: Yes.

28:55.575 --> 28:57.210
Why?

28:58.004 --> 29:01.104
Well, scientists think
that light travels

29:01.105 --> 29:03.149
through its own special,
invisible medium.

29:03.150 --> 29:04.394
They call it the ether.

29:04.395 --> 29:05.674
Yeah, but if it's invisible,

29:05.675 --> 29:07.878
- then how do we know it's there?
- We don't.

29:07.879 --> 29:09.861
People have been trying
to understand this for years.

29:09.862 --> 29:12.544
We can't...
We can't see it o-or feel it,

29:12.545 --> 29:14.270
but everywhere that light travels,

29:14.271 --> 29:15.612
the ether is there.

29:15.613 --> 29:16.540
That sounds

29:16.541 --> 29:17.818
pretty fantastical.

29:17.819 --> 29:18.744
- I agree.
- (both chuckle)

29:18.745 --> 29:21.142
But it's the best idea we've got.

29:21.143 --> 29:22.932
A wave needs a medium.

29:22.933 --> 29:24.753
But why?

29:24.754 --> 29:28.493
I don't know.

29:28.494 --> 29:30.985
But I intend to find out.

29:30.986 --> 29:33.862
Damn fine show, Einstein.

29:33.863 --> 29:35.364
(mouths)

29:35.365 --> 29:36.674
(baby cries)

29:36.675 --> 29:38.432
Shh, shh, shh, shh.

29:38.433 --> 29:40.732
(children yelling, laughing)

29:40.733 --> 29:42.778
I don't know how you do it, Helene.

29:42.779 --> 29:44.696
(chuckles)

29:44.697 --> 29:46.581
They turn out to be more of a delight

29:46.582 --> 29:48.946
than you can possibly imagine.

29:48.947 --> 29:51.215
What if I don't want children?

29:51.216 --> 29:53.037
Well, it's a bit late for that.

29:53.038 --> 29:56.712
(baby fusses)

29:56.713 --> 29:58.885
I don't know if I can count on Albert.

29:58.886 --> 30:00.066
Well, you can always

30:00.067 --> 30:01.441
count on me,

30:01.442 --> 30:03.168
Mileva.

30:03.169 --> 30:07.391
You've always been my
closest friend, Helene.

30:08.185 --> 30:11.738
And you love children.

30:12.531 --> 30:15.413
What if you took my baby?

30:17.773 --> 30:20.616
No, Mileva...

30:20.617 --> 30:23.690
Everything I've worked for...

30:25.060 --> 30:26.977
(chuckles)

30:26.978 --> 30:29.533
Forget I said that.

30:29.534 --> 30:31.482
It's horrid.

30:31.483 --> 30:34.237
I haven't been sleeping... (chuckles)

30:35.862 --> 30:38.322
(baby fusses)

30:38.323 --> 30:40.238
If it is what you need, Mileva...

30:40.239 --> 30:43.627
If it is what you <i>really</i> need...

30:43.628 --> 30:46.663
I will help you.

30:46.664 --> 30:49.097
(breathing raggedly)

30:54.078 --> 30:56.352
(cries)

30:59.574 --> 31:02.040
(sobs)

31:04.209 --> 31:06.861
(Mileva screams, gasps)

31:06.862 --> 31:09.231
(panting)

31:11.080 --> 31:12.747
("Maple Leaf Rag" playing on piano)

31:14.180 --> 31:16.512
(giggles)

31:16.513 --> 31:17.924
(guests laughing)

31:20.604 --> 31:23.127
SOLOVINE: Do you ever feel
like you're part

31:23.128 --> 31:25.817
of something larger?

31:26.609 --> 31:27.889
Yes. The universe is so vast.

31:27.890 --> 31:29.487
Lately, we've been
trying to measure it,

31:29.488 --> 31:31.469
- but so far...
- Albert, Jesus.

31:31.470 --> 31:32.555
I'm talking about

31:32.556 --> 31:33.706
the three of us.

31:33.707 --> 31:34.888
We should codify

31:34.889 --> 31:36.070
our little salon.

31:36.071 --> 31:37.190
We'll meet regularly...

31:37.191 --> 31:38.627
- Nightly.
- Nightly. Fine.

31:38.628 --> 31:41.599
With the express purpose of
ruminating on philosophy,

31:41.600 --> 31:43.357
science, music, art...

31:43.358 --> 31:45.113
And women.

31:45.114 --> 31:48.022
- (laughs)
- And women, too.

31:48.023 --> 31:50.547
But we need a name for
our little association.

31:50.548 --> 31:53.199
The honor is yours, Einstein.

31:53.200 --> 31:54.605
You made this possible.

31:54.606 --> 31:56.274
Well, uh, how about...

31:57.356 --> 31:59.017
the Olympia Academy.

31:59.018 --> 32:01.828
SOLOVINE AND HABICHT:
The Olympia Academy.

32:01.829 --> 32:03.522
(chuckles) Grand and ridiculous,

32:03.523 --> 32:06.047
equal parts pompous and austere.

32:06.048 --> 32:07.422
Just like its founding members.

32:07.423 --> 32:08.635
(all laugh)

32:08.636 --> 32:11.098
Long live the Olympia Academy.

32:11.099 --> 32:12.503
The Olympia Academy.

32:12.504 --> 32:13.653
(chuckles)

32:13.654 --> 32:15.128
(baby cries)

32:32.100 --> 32:34.008
MILOS: She's the most beautiful girl

32:34.009 --> 32:35.384
in the entire world.

32:35.385 --> 32:37.653
Elizabeth.

32:37.654 --> 32:40.146
Little Lieserl.

32:40.147 --> 32:42.766
That's what I told Albert
I want to call her.

32:42.767 --> 32:44.236
Where is he?

32:44.237 --> 32:46.729
Wherever is your father, sweet Lieserl?

32:46.730 --> 32:48.077
(door closes)

32:49.287 --> 32:51.880
(man and woman laugh)

32:54.720 --> 32:57.594
SOLOVINE: Don't linger
in the doorway, Einstein.

32:57.595 --> 32:59.097
Didn't your mother
teach you any manners?

32:59.098 --> 33:00.758
I only came to say

33:00.759 --> 33:02.868
that I won't be attending
this evening's festivities.

33:02.869 --> 33:04.305
Why not?

33:04.306 --> 33:05.711
I have a family matter.

33:05.712 --> 33:06.607
Somebody died?

33:06.608 --> 33:07.980
Ah!

33:07.981 --> 33:11.848
And you're inheriting a
tropical island nation, yes?

33:11.849 --> 33:13.094
(chuckles)

33:13.095 --> 33:14.693
I'll return in a few weeks.

33:14.694 --> 33:16.673
- Where are you going?
- Serbia.

33:16.674 --> 33:18.432
Serbia?

33:18.433 --> 33:19.870
Einstein...

33:19.871 --> 33:21.754
look in here

33:21.755 --> 33:24.600
and tell me Serbia is more important

33:24.601 --> 33:25.910
than what you see.

33:25.911 --> 33:27.763
Now, go on, tell me.

33:27.764 --> 33:29.622
What's this all about?

33:31.791 --> 33:34.091
I just became a father.

33:34.092 --> 33:35.754
Are you married?

33:35.755 --> 33:38.980
I'm not married to her.

33:38.981 --> 33:40.865
Hmm.

33:40.866 --> 33:43.104
(grunts) Allow me to indulge
in a little thought experiment.

33:43.105 --> 33:47.833
- Just imagine a full and
turbulent household.

33:47.834 --> 33:49.655
A newborn child,

33:49.656 --> 33:52.147
cawing, soiling herself left and right.

33:52.148 --> 33:55.886
Sleepless nights, chaotic days.

33:55.887 --> 33:58.699
A late rent payment, a haggard wife,

33:58.700 --> 34:00.361
nagging her untidy husband...

34:00.362 --> 34:01.800
- Maurice...
- Stay with me now.

34:01.801 --> 34:04.107
This is where it turns naughty.

34:05.476 --> 34:06.848
Your colleagues.

34:06.849 --> 34:08.382
Can you see them?

34:08.384 --> 34:11.322
Huh? Men of inferior intellect.

34:11.322 --> 34:14.773
But untethered by family,
they go zipping past you

34:14.774 --> 34:16.020
at the speed of light.

34:16.021 --> 34:18.322
And you're left...

34:18.322 --> 34:21.485
holding a mewling newborn,
asking yourself, "How the hell

34:21.485 --> 34:24.233
did I get here?"

34:24.234 --> 34:25.991
It's not as if I can turn back time.

34:25.992 --> 34:27.621
- Why are you torturing me?
- My cousin

34:27.623 --> 34:29.603
has a perfectly agreeable situation.

34:29.605 --> 34:31.744
He sends the mother
of his boy a stipend

34:31.745 --> 34:33.534
every month.

34:33.534 --> 34:35.036
Everybody happy.

34:35.036 --> 34:36.315
You're talking

34:36.315 --> 34:37.465
about a woman that I love

34:37.466 --> 34:39.349
and the child she just
brought into the world.

34:39.350 --> 34:41.427
I... Are you suggesting I abandon them?

34:41.428 --> 34:42.705
Abandon? No.

34:42.706 --> 34:44.303
Send money. Provide help.

34:44.304 --> 34:46.158
But you must not sacrifice your dreams

34:46.159 --> 34:48.683
just to make them happy.

34:48.684 --> 34:51.079
Albert.

34:51.080 --> 34:54.723
You are the most
brilliant man I've ever met.

34:54.724 --> 34:57.024
You're going to do great things.

34:57.025 --> 35:00.027
But not if you cinch an anchor

35:00.028 --> 35:01.855
around your neck.

35:05.813 --> 35:09.749
Think about it, Albert.

35:19.810 --> 35:21.408
Maja?

35:21.409 --> 35:23.868
What are you doing here?

35:23.869 --> 35:25.595
I wrote. You didn't answer.

35:25.596 --> 35:27.033
What is it?

35:27.034 --> 35:28.951
It's Father.

35:28.952 --> 35:31.123
He's very sick, Albert.

35:31.124 --> 35:32.919
We must go now.

35:37.719 --> 35:39.635
(knocking)

35:39.636 --> 35:41.399
Herr Professor.

35:45.324 --> 35:48.142
- Thank you.
- Yes, sir.

36:02.774 --> 36:04.691
- (shouts)
- (shattering)

36:04.692 --> 36:07.663
EINSTEIN: <i>They're giving it
to a man named Rontgen.</i>

36:07.664 --> 36:09.580
He's discovered what
they're calling X-rays.

36:09.581 --> 36:11.562
- Perhaps you read about it, Papa.
- Yeah?

36:11.563 --> 36:14.246
The Nobel is a major new prize.

36:14.247 --> 36:17.959
Maybe you will win one someday, yes?

36:19.681 --> 36:20.957
Hmm.

36:20.958 --> 36:22.716
No. (chuckles)

36:22.717 --> 36:25.016
You were right about
me all along, Papa.

36:25.017 --> 36:28.756
I'm... I'm only a dreamer.

36:28.757 --> 36:30.871
No.

36:31.633 --> 36:36.239
No, that's not true.

36:43.010 --> 36:45.310
(gulps) I...

36:45.311 --> 36:48.314
I've never told you this, Papa, but...

36:48.315 --> 36:50.488
when I'm lost,

36:50.489 --> 36:53.588
it's always your voice
I hear in my head.

36:53.589 --> 36:55.824
Guiding me.

36:55.825 --> 36:59.820
Maja told me you were
angry about the letter

36:59.821 --> 37:01.417
I sent to your professor.

37:01.418 --> 37:04.485
I was only trying to help.

37:04.486 --> 37:06.084
I know.

37:06.085 --> 37:08.096
It was childish of me. I'm so sorry.

37:08.097 --> 37:09.120
It wasn't you

37:09.121 --> 37:11.995
- I was angry with.
- (shushing)

37:11.996 --> 37:14.457
Tell me about the girl.

37:14.458 --> 37:16.374
The Serb.

37:16.375 --> 37:18.356
(chuckles softly)
Mother doesn't approve.

37:18.357 --> 37:19.730
(scoffs)

37:19.731 --> 37:21.584
Do you love her?

37:21.585 --> 37:25.642
Yes. But it's very complicated.

37:25.643 --> 37:28.614
You're a complex soul, Albert.

37:28.615 --> 37:30.307
(sniffles)

37:30.308 --> 37:32.225
If you've found a woman

37:32.226 --> 37:35.900
who will abide with your peculiarities,

37:35.901 --> 37:40.056
well, miracles
should not be sniffed at.

37:40.057 --> 37:42.522
(sniffling)

37:43.284 --> 37:45.967
Marry her.

37:45.968 --> 37:48.492
Marry her.

37:48.493 --> 37:52.360
(gasps Have a big family.

37:52.361 --> 37:54.820
Huh?

37:54.821 --> 37:56.737
(gasps)

37:56.738 --> 37:59.678
The one true blessing in this world

37:59.679 --> 38:03.577
is family.

38:03.578 --> 38:06.421
(gasping)

38:06.422 --> 38:09.200
(exhales)

38:09.201 --> 38:10.958
Leave now.

38:10.959 --> 38:13.196
Go

38:13.197 --> 38:16.365
I'd like to die alone.

38:18.438 --> 38:20.903
(sniffles)

38:25.725 --> 38:28.222
(sniffles)

38:46.051 --> 38:48.510
(Einstein saying kaddish)

38:48.511 --> 38:50.428
ALL: Amen.

38:50.429 --> 38:53.597
(continues saying kaddish)

39:06.345 --> 39:07.909
ALL: Amen.

39:07.910 --> 39:10.179
(priest blessing in Serbian)

39:10.180 --> 39:13.253
(crying)

39:17.498 --> 39:20.027
(shushing softly)

39:24.432 --> 39:26.765
(coughs)

39:26.766 --> 39:29.385
(cries)

39:29.386 --> 39:31.915
(coughing)

39:35.298 --> 39:37.790
- (crying)
- (shushes, gasps)

39:37.791 --> 39:41.407
(speaking indistinctly)

39:45.045 --> 39:48.118
(knocking)

39:57.584 --> 39:58.926
Yes?

39:58.927 --> 40:01.999
<i>Telegramma per Albert Einstein.</i>

40:05.253 --> 40:07.750
Thank you.

40:14.267 --> 40:16.796
(bell tolling)

40:19.731 --> 40:22.227
(priest praying in Serbian)

40:34.016 --> 40:36.481
(crying)

40:46.992 --> 40:49.488
(sobbing)

40:57.921 --> 41:00.126
Perhaps it's for the best.

41:00.127 --> 41:02.298
How could you say such a thing?

41:02.299 --> 41:04.408
It is sad, yes,

41:04.409 --> 41:06.933
but you no longer have any
obligation to marry this girl.

41:06.934 --> 41:09.074
Papa gave it his blessing.

41:09.075 --> 41:10.991
Papa is dead.

41:10.992 --> 41:12.684
You told me

41:12.685 --> 41:14.794
that your life was
just getting started.

41:14.795 --> 41:16.935
Now, here you are,

41:16.936 --> 41:20.420
free to pursue your dreams
with no responsibilities.

41:20.421 --> 41:23.135
MILOS: <i>Perhaps this is
God's way of giving you</i>

41:23.136 --> 41:25.309
another chance. Perhaps it's...

41:25.310 --> 41:27.546
Lieserl's gift to you.

41:27.547 --> 41:29.942
You're still young.

41:29.943 --> 41:32.338
You don't need a man.

41:32.339 --> 41:34.256
You never did.

41:34.257 --> 41:36.366
EINSTEIN: <i>What about Mileva?</i>

41:36.367 --> 41:39.530
Maybe this is what
is right for her, too.

41:39.531 --> 41:41.767
I know you, brother. You can barely...

41:41.768 --> 41:44.035
dress yourself,
let alone raise a family.

41:44.036 --> 41:45.794
That isn't true.

41:45.795 --> 41:49.213
You have your eyes set
on the stars, Albert.

41:49.214 --> 41:51.898
It's who you are.
It's what makes you wonderful.

41:51.899 --> 41:54.295
But think about her life.

41:54.296 --> 41:57.170
Here, on Earth.

41:57.171 --> 41:59.280
MILOS: <i>Now you can do anything,</i>

41:59.281 --> 42:01.166
be anybody,

42:01.167 --> 42:03.696
go anywhere.

42:04.937 --> 42:07.434
(train chugging)

42:09.572 --> 42:12.070
(indistinct chatter)

42:36.289 --> 42:39.490
How could you not have come?

42:41.850 --> 42:43.958
I'm so sorry, Dollie.

42:43.959 --> 42:47.442
(sniffles) My father
became ill so fast.

42:47.443 --> 42:50.611
If I had had any idea...

42:51.437 --> 42:54.153
When I saw her

42:54.154 --> 42:58.627
being lowered into the ground...

42:58.628 --> 43:02.206
it was like a piece
of me was torn away.

43:02.207 --> 43:04.539
A piece of me buried alongside her.

43:04.540 --> 43:06.777
And I knew

43:06.778 --> 43:10.931
the only person who
could fill that void...

43:10.932 --> 43:13.488
is you.

43:13.489 --> 43:17.297
And I hate you for that.

43:19.241 --> 43:22.117
Go on hating me if you choose.

43:22.118 --> 43:24.258
I know I deserve it.

43:24.259 --> 43:26.654
And I know I...

43:26.655 --> 43:29.210
I don't deserve you.

43:29.211 --> 43:32.247
But I will never feel anything

43:32.248 --> 43:35.736
but love for you, Mileva.

43:39.055 --> 43:40.651
Marry me, Dollie.

43:40.652 --> 43:45.318
I know it might only be a
humble life I have to offer,

43:45.319 --> 43:47.875
but... (sniffles) it's a good life.

43:47.876 --> 43:49.218
And if we're together,

43:49.219 --> 43:52.898
then it couldn't
possibly be anything else.

43:56.984 --> 43:59.481
♪ ♪

44:03.344 --> 44:05.900
KATHARINA: It's only
the very first Nobel.

44:05.901 --> 44:09.318
You will win the next one.
I believe in you, Philipp.

44:09.319 --> 44:10.165
You're a genius.

44:10.166 --> 44:12.611
It's bigger than you
understand, Katharina.

44:12.612 --> 44:14.464
This whole charade, it's...

44:14.465 --> 44:16.541
more evidence of a troubling trend.

44:16.542 --> 44:17.725
And what's that?

44:17.726 --> 44:19.642
This avaricious hunger
for money and acclaim.

44:19.643 --> 44:21.655
It's-it's a disease.

44:21.656 --> 44:23.860
It's the Jewish mind-set.

44:23.861 --> 44:25.394
I didn't know Rontgen was Jewish.

44:25.395 --> 44:27.472
He isn't. But I've worked with them.

44:27.473 --> 44:29.772
I know their hearts.

44:29.773 --> 44:32.425
And Rontgen has a Jewish heart.

44:32.426 --> 44:33.928
He's a rat,

44:33.929 --> 44:35.525
like the Jews.

44:35.526 --> 44:39.398
And rats must be eradicated.

44:43.036 --> 44:46.679
You'll come up with
something marvelous, Philipp.

44:46.680 --> 44:48.794
I know it.

44:57.577 --> 44:58.951
(crackling)

44:58.952 --> 45:00.746
♪ ♪

45:12.150 --> 45:14.483
(grunts softly)

45:14.484 --> 45:17.102
Well, good morning, Frau Einstein.

45:17.103 --> 45:18.323
Mm.

45:19.437 --> 45:21.640
What has you so riveted this early?

45:21.641 --> 45:22.823
Philipp Lenard.

45:22.824 --> 45:24.038
<i>He's demonstrated</i>

45:24.039 --> 45:25.667
<i>something interesting in the emissions</i>

45:25.668 --> 45:27.809
<i>of metals when bombarded with light:</i>

45:27.810 --> 45:29.502
more intense light

45:29.503 --> 45:31.419
does not produce
more energetic emissions.

45:31.420 --> 45:33.019
Well, he is a brilliant man.

45:33.020 --> 45:34.936
But he didn't go far enough.

45:34.937 --> 45:37.237
He gives no explanation as to why.

45:37.238 --> 45:39.409
Something more is needed.
Something revolutionary.

45:39.410 --> 45:40.593
If I had the time...

45:40.594 --> 45:42.511
Well, right now you don't.

45:42.512 --> 45:45.041
You're going to be late.

45:57.371 --> 45:59.868
(bell tolling)

46:18.113 --> 46:20.419
(door shuts)

46:24.184 --> 46:26.649
(soft chattering)

46:32.974 --> 46:36.046
Herr Einstein,
welcome to the patent office.

46:55.984 --> 46:58.513
(indistinct chatter)

47:15.574 --> 47:18.039
(stamping, chattering increase
in volume)

